http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Used to describe the legal access for highways and other transportation networks.
Only for agricultural traffic.
This road has an asphalt surface.
Usable by trekking bikes, normal cars and everything that can use roads with 'very bad' smoothness.
A barrier is a physical structure which blocks or impedes movement.
This is not a oneway street.
A large, solid, immobile block that can be moved only with heavy machinery or great effort.
Solid (usually concrete or metal) pillar or pillars in the middle of the road to prevent passage by some traffic.
This is a control point at an international border between two countries. Passports or other forms of ID will be checked.
A way intended for use by horse riders.
A bump gate is a drive-through gate used in rural areas to provide a barrier to livestock that does not require the driver to exit the vehicle.

A bus trap is a metal grate placed over a ditch or pit in the road with tines (sides) spaced far enough apart that small-diameter-wheeled (narrower axle) vehicles fall in between the tines but close enough that larger-diameter-wheeled vehicles, such as buses, may pass.
Bars in the road surface that allow wheeled vehicles but not animals to cross.
A chain used to prevent motorised vehicles.
This road has an cobblestone surface.
A mixture of larger (e.g., gravel) and smaller (e.g., sand) parts, compacted so the surface is more stable than loose gravel.
Cement based concrete.
Used to describe a feature which is currently under construction.
This tag is used for more accurately describing specific types of pedestrian crossings.
Only for customers of the element.
Barriers to bicycle traffic, most typically a pair of staggered steel bars perpendicular to the way itself whose gaps allow pedestrians to pass.
For designated cycleways.
Maps cycling infrastructure that is an inherent part of the road.
A road is blocked by debris with or without ground. This might be for short or long time. Often used as first step in blocking an abandoned road.
Only when delivering to the element.
A preferred or designated route.
Only when travelling to this element/area; i.e., local traffic only.
This road's surface is just dirt (earth).
A legal right of way exists but usage is officially discouraged.
Permitted for some vehicle (or animal) only if you dismount.
Elements are the basic components of OpenStreetMap's conceptual data model of the physical world.
Only for emergency vehicles.
A gap in a linear barrier with nothing that limits passing through.
Usable by roller blades, skate boards and everything that can use roads with 'good' smoothness.
A multilayer pavement with a stone or gravel basis and a topmost surface of firm, granular gravel.
Designated footpaths; i.e., mainly/exclusively for pedestrians.
Refines the osm:Footway for sidewalks.
Only for forestry traffic.
The public has an official, legally-enshrined right of access; i.e., it's a right of way.
An entrance that can be opened or closed to get through the barrier.
Points where a traffic sign instructs traffic to cede priority.
Usable by racing bikes and everything that can use roads with 'intermediate' smoothness.
Solid. Usually a paved or sealed surface.
Solid. Usually an unpaved track with surface of gravel.
Mostly solid. Even mixture of hard and soft materials.
Mostly soft. Almost always an unpaved track prominently with soil/sand/grass, but with some hard or compacted materials mixed in.
Soft. Almost always an unpaved track lacking additional materials, same surface as surrounding terrain.
Grass covered ground.
Broken/crushed rock with sharp edges.
No special surface, the ground itself has marks of human or animal usage.
Pedestrians can cross a street here.
Indicates the role and importance of the way within the road network.
Usable by heavy-duty off-road vehicles and everything that can use roads with 'very horrible' smoothness.
Not usable by wheeled vehicles.
This is a oneway street, with the direction being the same order of the way nodes.
This is a oneway street, with the direction being the reverse of the order of the way nodes.
Usable by city bikes, sport cars, wheel chairs and everything that can use roads with 'bad' smoothness.
Two-way streets where there are cycle lanes on both sides of the road.
A lift gate (boom barrier) is a bar, or pole pivoted in such a way as to allow the boom to block vehicular access through a controlled point.
For living streets, which are residential streets where pedestrians have legal priority over cars.
A restricted access major divided highway, normally with 2 or more running lanes plus emergency hard shoulder.
The link roads leading to/from a motorway.
Like the ground surface, but usually wet.
No access for the general public.

A node is one of the core elements in the OpenStreetMap data model.
                              It consists of a single point in space defined by its latitude, longitude and node id.
A way legally dedicated to specific modes of travel by a law or by the rules of traffic.
Indicate the access restriction on highways and other linear features.
Cyclists are permitted to travel in both directions on a road which is one-way for normal traffic.
A one-way street that has a cycling lane going in the opposite direction to normal traffic flow.
A cycle track travelling in the opposite direction to other traffic.
A non-specific path.
A non-specific paved surface.
A relatively smooth surface paved with stones.
Loosely arranged smooth stones.
Open to general traffic until such time as the owner revokes the permission.
The next most important roads in a country's system, after trunks.
The link roads leading to/from a primary road.
Only with individual permission.
For roads that are about to be built, but where any construction work hasn't yet been started.

A relation consists of one or more tags and also an ordered list of one or more nodes, ways and/or relations as members.
                              It is used to define logical or geographic relationships between other elements.
Roads which serve as an access to housing, without function of connecting settlements. Often lined with housing.
This tag is used for a road with an unknown classification.
A sally port is used to pass through thick or city walls, and is a type of covered gate with two doors.
Small to very small fractions of rock.
The next most important roads in a country's system, after primary roads.
The link roads leading to/from a secondary road.
For access roads to, or within an industrial estate, camp site, business park, car park etc.
Sett paving, formed from natural stones cut to a regular shape. The stones do not cover the surface completely, unlike paving_stones.
A cycle lane taking the form of a bus lane that is also designated for use by cyclists.
In general, this indicates that cyclists share space with other traffic on this highway.
Roads which contain a shared lane marking, or sharrow, to indicate that the travel lane is shared by bicycles and other vehicles.
A sidewalk that's distinct from the carriageway.
Provides a classification scheme regarding the physical usability of a way.
Flights of steps on footways and paths.
Points at which vehicles are required to stop.
Provides information about the physical surface of elements, particularly regarding material composition and/or structure.
Similar to a lift gate but rotates sidewards to open.
The next most important roads in a country's system, after secondary roads.
The link roads leading to/from a tertiary road.
A road usage toll or fee is collected here.
Roads for mostly agricultural or forestry uses. If used in the context of a cycleway this means a cycle track running parallel to a road.
Measures how well-maintained a track is, particularly regarding surface firmness.
Signalling devices positioned at road intersections, pedestrian crossings and other locations to control competing flows of traffic.
The most important roads in a country's system that aren't motorways.
The link roads leading to/from a trunk road.
A turnstile (also called baffle gate) is used to allow one person at a time to pass.
The least important through roads in a country's system.
A generic crossing with no traffic-signals of any type, just road markings.
Indicates that this element is under construction.
Cobblestone paving, formed from natural, uncut, overall rounded stones. Firmly attached to a ground, unlike pebblestone.
A crossing without road markings or traffic lights
A loose covering ranging from compacted stone chippings to earth.
Can only be used in countries with compulsory cycleways and gives access information on parallel roads.
Usable by cars with high clearance, light-duty off-road vehicles and everything that can use roads with 'horrible' smoothness.
Usable by tractors, ATVs and tanks.
A way is an ordered list of nodes which normally also has at least one tag.
Wood.
Used to describe the legal access for highways and other transportation networks.
A barrier is a physical structure which blocks or impedes movement.
Legal restrictions for bicycles.
Used to describe a feature which is currently under construction.
This tag is used for more accurately describing specific types of pedestrian crossings.
Maps cycling infrastructure that is an inherent part of the road.
Refines the osm:Footway for sidewalks.

An ordered collection of nodes that describe the way. 
                              These may be fragmented over multiple predicates due to tiling for example.
                              Each fragment should have enough overlap to reconstruct the original way.

A tag describes the meaning of a particular element in the OSM data model. 
                              It consists of two free format text fields; a 'key' and a 'value' and are formatted as '{key}={value}'. 
                              This property should be used for tags that don't have their semantics explicitly defined.
This the main property used to identify any kind of road, street or path.
Used to define the maximum legal speed limit, in km/h.
Legal access restriction for all motor vehicles.
Legal access permission for cars.
Used for naming an element.
Indicate the access restriction on highways and other linear features.
Defines the oneway rules for cyclists.
Used for combined cycle- and footways.
Provides a classification scheme regarding the physical usability of a way.
Provides information about the physical surface of elements, particularly regarding material composition and/or structure.
Measures how well-maintained a track is, particularly regarding surface firmness.
Legal access restriction for all types of land-based vehicles not operated upon rails.
